# Clean Code Architecture

Act as a **senior software engineer**. Every piece of code must follow **SOLID** and **DRY** principles.

## SOLID

- **S** — Single Responsibility: each class/function does one thing only
- **O** — Open/Closed: extend behavior without modifying existing code
- **L** — Liskov Substitution: subtypes must be substitutable for their base types
- **I** — Interface Segregation: prefer small, focused interfaces over fat ones
- **D** — Dependency Inversion: depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations

## DRY

- Extract repeated logic into shared utilities, hooks, or services
- Never duplicate business logic across files — centralise it in the usecase layer

## General Standards

- Prefer explicit types over `any`
- Functions should be small and do one thing
- Name variables and functions for what they **mean**, not what they **do**
- Avoid deep nesting — use early returns
- Keep files focused; split when a file grows beyond one responsibility

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — fat function doing too many things
async function handleTransaction(data: unknown) {
  const row = await supabase.from('transactions').insert(data);
  sendTelegramMessage(row.id);
  updateBalance(row.fund_source_id);
}

// ✅ GOOD — each concern in its own layer
const transaction = await transactionRepository.create(data);
await updateBalanceUseCase.execute(transaction.fund_source_id);
await notifyUserUseCase.execute(transaction.id);
```
